string is a CLASSS

to find the length of any strings

eg:

"Test".length();

or we can also do,  String str = "Test";
str.length();

to access the individual letters, 

str.charAt(index);
==> str.charAt(0) ====> T

suppose, str = "hello i am kaushik"

if we type in,

str.substring(5)    ===> " i am kaushik"

we can also use,

str.substring(1,5)  ===> "ell"  1 is included but 5 isnt

we can also search for the characters, 

str.indexOf('i');

if there might be repeitions, we can use this too

str.lastIndexOf('i');

we can also check the starting and the end,

str.startsWith("hello");    ====> here false, as the case wont match
str.endsWith("kaushik");    ====> here its true

similarily, there is equals and equalsIgnoreCase

eg,

    "text".equals("text");  true
    "text".equals("Text");  false
    "text".equalsIgnoreCase("Text");  true

    [we can use strings in place of the content as well]

we also got concatenation

string str = "Hi";

string newe = str.concat(" Helllooo");
newe ==> Hi Helllooo

========================================================

1 + 2                   =           3
"1" + "2"               =          "12"
1 + 2 + "3"             =          "33"
"1" + 2 + 3             =          "123"

========================================================


there is also join and replace methods


String.join(",","A","B","C");           ==>     "A,B,C"
String.join(".","1","2","3");           ==>     "1.2.3"

"abad".replace('a','z');                ==>     "zbzd"

